        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Preference Centers for AI and Claude Settings"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A preference center gives users direct control over how Claude-powered features behave for them: which features are active, how long conversation history is retained, whether their interactions feed analytics, and stylistic settings like tone and language. Unlike a one-time consent dialog, a preference center is a persistent self-service UI backed by a stored preferences object that other parts of the system read at runtime."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Preference center architecture showing UI, API, store, audit log, and consumers",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The architecture above separates preference capture (the browser UI and the REST API) from preference storage (the database) and preference consumption (the API gate, prompt builder, retention engine, and analytics pipeline). A change event propagates to all consumers so that a user toggling off a feature takes effect within 500ms without requiring a page reload or a new login."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Preference Schema"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Define preferences as a flat, versioned key-value map. Flat structures are easier to serialize, cache, and diff than deeply nested objects, and they map naturally to feature-flag systems."
          }
        ]
      },
